Here’s what caught our attention on Friday: 1. MTN Ghana results Telecommunications company, MTN‘s Ghana unit released its results for the nine months ended September 30, 2018, in which it reported service revenue growth of 22.9%, a data revenue increase of 30.9% and a digital revenue increase of 28%. The company’s basic earnings per share is at 0.05 cents from 0.04 cents the previous year. The board has declared a gross interim dividend of GHS 0.02 per share. Read: MTN Ghana revenue rises, driven by mobile money service 2. Cartrack trading statement Cartrack issued a trading statement for the six months ended August 31, 2018 (HY19) in which it says it expects headline earnings per share and basic earnings per share to increase between 20% and 30% to 56 and 60 cents, respectively. The company expects to release its results on October 31, 2018. 3. Kingon to testify at Nugent Commission Acting Sars commissioner, Mark Kingon will be testifying at the Nugent Commission of Inquiry into tax administration and governance at Sars on Friday. Earlier this week, President Cyril Ramaphosa released Judge Nugent’s interim report in which he said that suspended Sars commissioner, Tom Moyane should be removed from office. 4. Investment summit to land in SA A day after the presentation of the medium-term budget policy statement on October 24, 2018, around 1 000 investors will flock to Sandton to attend President Cyril Ramaphosa’s Investment Summit. Investors will have the opportunity to engage directly with regulators and cabinet ministers to find ways to unlock money and get the economy back on track. The summit will commence on Thursday and conclude on Saturday. Read: Davos is coming to Sandton 5. Rand update The worry surrounding the rand is easing (knocks wood). On Friday, the rand was at R14.37 to the dollar at 8:59 am.